shorewall-nft (0.1.3) unstable; urgency=medium

  * Fixes found reviewing 0.1.2, and the config-form coverage was extended with
    SOURCE and DEST forms from shorewall-addresses(5) and shorewall-exclusion(5)
    so these cannot regress unseen:
    - a $FW-sourced REDIRECT or DNAT (the transparent-proxy pattern) is emitted
      in the output nat hook, where it belongs, rather than being rejected.
    - an accounting SOURCE or DEST of the interface:address form is scoped by
      both, not rejected as an address.
    - a tc RATE or CEIL of full is accepted in any case.
    - a policy all!zone exclusion is not implemented yet; it now fails with a
      clear message rather than a misleading unknown-zone error.

  * A blacklist rule on a zone with several interfaces including a wildcard
    emits one rule per interface rather than a set of name globs, which nft
    1.0.2 mishandles and which silently failed the blacklist open.

  * geoip: the refill batch budget is halved for the interval set (its netlink
    message roughly doubles), so a large country stays under one transaction.

 -- Dave Kempe <dave@sol1.com.au>  Mon, 20 Jul 2026 12:04:48 +1000

shorewall-nft (0.1.2) unstable; urgency=medium

  * Fixes found reviewing 0.1.1, and a coverage suite for documented config
    forms so they cannot regress unseen again. More documented forms that had
    stopped compiling or loading now work:
    - CONNLIMIT: a negated !limit emitted the invalid nft keyword 'until', so
      the ruleset failed to load; the direction was also inverted. A plain
      limit now matches at or below N, a !limit above N, matching upstream.
    - policy all+/any+ is honored: it overrides the implicit intra-zone accept
      as upstream does, rather than aborting the compile or being ignored.
    - accounting SOURCE/DEST of any or all is accepted again.
    - a tcpri ADDRESS may be a ~MAC address again.

  * A DNAT from a zone with no interface and no host is a located error rather
    than a silently dropped rule.

  * geoip: a set that fits one transaction is refilled atomically, a larger
    one is chunked under the netlink budget, and the restart path applies each
    batch as its own transaction, so a large country's set loads rather than
    silently failing and leaving a geoip rule open.

  * A TIME value must be plain digits (a sign or underscore is rejected).

 -- Dave Kempe <dave@sol1.com.au>  Mon, 20 Jul 2026 08:03:17 +1000

shorewall-nft (0.1.1) unstable; urgency=medium

  * Fixes found reviewing 0.1.0. Several 0.1.0 parse-boundary checks rejected
    valid configuration, which broke a migrating config. These compile again:
    a tc rate with an uppercase unit (10Mbit) or a '-' meaning the device
    bandwidth; a policy SOURCE or DEST of all+ or any+; a policy with a named
    default action (POLICY:action), now accepted and warned as not applied
    rather than rejected; and a CONNLIMIT with the documented d: prefix or a
    :mask, where the limit is enforced and the grouping is warned as not
    applied.

  * TIME rules now match local time. 0.1.0 emitted the window as a UTC second
    count, so a rule set for 17:00 fired at 03:00 on a UTC+10 host. The window
    is now the quoted local HH:MM form nft converts. A window that wraps
    midnight in UTC (a daytime range on a host east or west of UTC) cannot be
    one nft range and is reported at compile rather than matching at the wrong
    time.

  * A wildcard interface (ppp+) is globbed to ppp* everywhere it reaches the
    ruleset. 0.1.0 still emitted the literal ppp+ in the blacklist chain and
    in netmap, where a bare + became the invalid iifname "*"; nft never matched
    the former and rejected the latter.

  * A DNAT from a hosts-only zone is scoped by that zone's addresses again,
    not emitted open to every source.

  * An ACCOUNT entry whose SOURCE is a bare address counts that address, not
    an interface named after it. The rules and snat USER column, the ecn and
    tcpri interface and address columns, and the SNAT target are validated at
    the parse boundary, so a bad value is a located error rather than a ruleset
    nft refuses to load at start.

  * The geoip set refill is applied in transactions under the netlink budget,
    so a large country's set loads; a failed refill restores the previous
    contents rather than leaving the set empty and a geoip rule open.

 -- Dave Kempe <dave@sol1.com.au>  Mon, 20 Jul 2026 00:17:36 +1000

shorewall-nft (0.1.0) unstable; urgency=medium

  * First public release. The compiler turns a standard /etc/shorewall
    configuration into an nftables ruleset and a POSIX shell wrapper, applied
    with nft -f in one transaction. 31 of the 39 configuration files are
    supported. The remaining 6 fail with a clear error rather than drop
    silently.

  * Validate configuration tokens at the parse boundary, as upstream Shorewall
    does against its fixed character sets. Interface names and option values,
    addresses and networks, tc rates, packet marks, and provider, zone and set
    names are checked before they reach the generated shell script or the
    ruleset. This keeps a stray metacharacter in a config field out of the
    commands the wrapper runs as root. It matters wherever the configuration,
    or a value written into it, is not fully trusted: a templated or generated
    config, or a file that is not root-owned and root-only. See
    REQUIRE_SECURE_CONFIG.

  * REQUIRE_SECURE_CONFIG. The compiler warns when a configuration file is
    group- or world-writable, or not owned by root. Set it to Yes to make that
    an error. The token validation above is always on; this setting governs
    only the file-permission check, so migration is unaffected.

  * Report malformed configuration as a located error naming the file and line,
    not a Python traceback. A bad number, an unknown directive, an unsupported
    verdict or disposition, a missing INCLUDE file and the like now fail the
    way the rest of the compiler does.

  * The implicit intra-zone ACCEPT now applies the configured ACCEPT_DEFAULT
    action, so its broadcast and multicast drops are no longer silently
    skipped.

  * The TIME column emits the forms nft loads: full weekday names for meta day
    and a second count for meta hour. A range that crosses midnight is a clear
    error rather than a ruleset nft rejects.

  * A per-source-subnet CONNLIMIT mask is rejected rather than silently applied
    as a single global limit. The anti-spoofing options sfilter, rpfilter and
    norfc1918 warn that they are not yet enforced, instead of passing as silent
    no-ops. maclist and blacklist audit dispositions render their audit log. An
    IPv6 rtrules source, a tc class rate or ceil of full, a bare-zone interface
    and the mangle MARK and TOS values are handled correctly.

  * A wildcard interface (ppp+) reaches the match as an nft name glob (ppp*)
    everywhere it is used: masq, snat, nat, the maclist and DNAT dispatch,
    mangle, tc priority and accounting. It was previously emitted as the
    literal ppp+, which nft never matches, so the rule silently did nothing.

  * A rules, policy or blrules entry that names an undeclared zone is a located
    error. Such a zone matched no chain, so the rule was silently dropped or a
    broader policy quietly took its place. A DNAT from all is emitted rather
    than dropped.

  * Add RPM packages. Test that the Debian and RPM packages install and compile
    a configuration across the Debian and Ubuntu families and the Red Hat
    family (Rocky, Alma, Fedora), covering roughly the last ten years of
    releases. Python 3.7 is the supported floor; older versions are tested but
    allowed to fail.

  * Expand the differential corpus (the upstream compiler against this one,
    with network-namespace behavioral probes), the proofs and the unit tests.
    Add coverage for shorewall migrate, the ruleset chunker, the TIME column,
    and a hardening suite that asserts each validation and error path.

 -- Dave Kempe <dave@sol1.com.au>  Sun, 19 Jul 2026 14:27:32 +1000

shorewall-nft (0.0.10) unstable; urgency=medium

  * Complete legacy Shorewall NETMAP compatibility for IPv4 and IPv6 using
    stateful nftables prefix NAT. Existing eight-column netmap files retain
    their TYPE, NET1, INTERFACE, NET2, NET3, PROTO, DPORT and SPORT layout.
  * Support equal-length prefix mapping, NET1 exclusions, logical and wildcard
    interfaces, optional packet qualifiers, service names, ICMP type/code
    matches, and provider-specific mappings distinguished by interface.
  * Validate address families, strict CIDR networks, prefix lengths,
    exclusions, interfaces, protocols, ports, duplicates and conflicting
    mappings before replacing the active ruleset.
  * Support SNAT, DNAT, SNAT:T and DNAT:P. Reject the historical cross-hook
    stateless SNAT:P and DNAT:T forms explicitly rather than silently changing
    their semantics. Document the conntrack and provider-failover differences
    from historical stateless Shorewall6 NETMAP.
  * Add parser, compiler, nft syntax and network-namespace behavioral tests,
    plus shorewall-netmap(5) and shorewall6-netmap(5) documentation.

 -- Dave Kempe <dave@sol1.com.au>  Mon, 13 Jul 2026 23:11:41 +1000

shorewall-nft (0.0.9) unstable; urgency=medium

  * shorewall show accounting reports when the counters were last cleared
    and how long they have been accumulating. The counters are zeroed
    whenever the ruleset is loaded, which is the state file's mtime.
  * The link monitor logs to the journal: a startup line naming the
    monitored providers, a per-provider heartbeat (state, latency, loss)
    at least once a minute, and every up or down transition. It also
    line-buffers its output, so the logs reach the journal promptly
    instead of sitting in a block buffer. Follow it with
    `journalctl -u shorewall-lsm -f`.

 -- Dave Kempe <dave@sol1.com.au>  Mon, 13 Jul 2026 00:00:02 +0000

shorewall-nft (0.0.8) unstable; urgency=medium

  * The multi-ISP routing seam is now family-aware. shorewall6 emitted
    `ip -4` commands for IPv6 providers, which errored on the IPv6 gateway
    ("inet prefix is expected") and, because routing tables are per-family
    but share numbers, flushed and could not rebuild the identically
    numbered IPv4 provider and balance tables. A shorewall6 start or reload
    therefore tore down a working IPv4 multi-ISP setup, sending traffic out
    the wrong provider. The seam now uses `ip -6`, `::/0` and IPv6 gateway
    detection for shorewall6, and saves the IPv6 default route on start.
    IPv4 output is unchanged.

 -- Dave Kempe <dave@sol1.com.au>  Mon, 13 Jul 2026 00:00:01 +0000

shorewall-nft (0.0.7) unstable; urgency=medium

  * Build the .deb with gzip compression, not the builder's default zstd.
    Debian 11 and other older releases ship a dpkg that cannot read a
    zstd-compressed .deb and fail the install with "unknown compression
    for member 'control.tar.zst'".
  * On Debian 11, preserve the running firewall across the package swap.
    The distro Shorewall 5.2.3.4 clears every rule when its package is
    removed (its service ExecStop is `shorewall clear`), which our install
    triggers, so the box would be left wide open until `shorewall migrate`.
    preinst snapshots the live ruleset and postinst restores it, or warns
    if it could not. Debian 12 and later dropped the clear-on-remove, so
    this is a no-op there.
  * Preserve externally populated nft sets across `shorewall stop` too, not
    just reload and start: the stopped-state table declares them and their
    elements are snapshotted and restored around the table replacement.
    stop now recompiles a fresh wrapper first, so an older generated
    artifact cannot retain destructive stop logic. (Lindsay Harvey)
  * Implement `shorewall show routing` and `shorewall6 show routing`, with
    the live policy rules and the standard, provider, balance and
    additional route tables in Shorewall-style output. (Lindsay Harvey)
  * Implement `shorewall show accounting` for live named counters,
    per-address counter sets and accounting chains. (Lindsay Harvey)
  * Accounting supports the CHAIN column, plain COUNT and DONE, and named
    accounting chains with per-direction counters. (Lindsay Harvey)
  * Fall back to chunked kernel validation when `shorewall check` or
    `shorewall migrate` hits the netlink transaction-size limit on a large
    generated ruleset. (Lindsay Harvey)

 -- Dave Kempe <dave@sol1.com.au>  Mon, 13 Jul 2026 00:00:00 +0000

shorewall-nft (0.0.6) unstable; urgency=medium

  * A source or destination column may again mix an address list with an
    ipset, MAC or geoip reference, for example 10.0.0.0/24,+knoc_ssh.
    Upstream fans a mixed column out into one rule per element, an OR; the
    compiler now does the same instead of rejecting it. A negated mixed
    column becomes an AND of exclusions in one rule, as upstream does.

